"# Chapter 15 — Performance introspection: time, fuel, memory

Motoi programs run under a fuel budget. `,time` reports wall time. The fuel counter reports how much of the budget was spent. Memory reporting shows allocation shape. All three are introspection surfaces on the cost of an expression.

This chapter teaches you to measure before you optimize.

## 15.1 ,time — wall time

`,time expr` at the REPL evaluates `expr` and prints how long it took.

```
> ,time (map (lambda (x) (* x x)) (range 1000))
=> (1 4 9 16 25 ...)
   (2.483 ms)
```

Same as Scheme's `(time ...)` idiom in most implementations. Wall time in milliseconds.

At programmatic level:

```scheme
(let ((t0 (current-time-ms)))
  (do-the-thing)
  (- (current-time-ms) t0))
;; => elapsed ms
```

## 15.2 Fuel — the evaluation budget

Every Motoi evaluation runs with a fuel counter. Each verb call deducts from the counter. When fuel runs out, evaluation errors with `fuel-exhausted`.

Default REPL fuel is 200000 units. You can query the current fuel:

```scheme
(current-fuel)
;; => 199847   ;; a bit spent
```

Or measure how much a specific expression burns:

```scheme
(let ((f0 (current-fuel)))
  (some-expression)
  (- f0 (current-fuel)))
;; => 42   ;; this expression burned 42 fuel
```

Fuel is a proxy for computational cost. Not perfect — some verbs cost more fuel than others based on estimated work — but a useful comparative measure.

## 15.3 Memory — allocation reporting

Motoi's memory introspection is coarser than time or fuel. You can ask for the current allocation count:

```scheme
(gc-info)
;; => (:allocated-bytes 1048576 :gc-runs 3 :last-gc-freed 262144)
```

For per-expression memory:

```scheme
(let ((m0 (allocated-bytes)))
  (some-expression)
  (- (allocated-bytes) m0))
;; => bytes allocated during expression
```

Memory introspection is useful for spotting allocation hot-spots. A verb that allocates ten megabytes when you expected kilobytes is a candidate for rewriting.

