## 15.20 A closing observation

Performance introspection is what turns *my code is slow* from a complaint into a diagnosis.

Without measurement, optimization is guessing. With measurement, optimization is bisecting. Chapter 15's verbs give you the measurement primitives; the rest is patience and iteration.

The introspection layer is not just for correctness debugging. It is also for performance debugging. Every axis of program behavior has a verb that reports it.

## 15.21 Deep-seed — the fuel philosophy

Motoi's fuel model is different from most languages. Fuel is not a resource that limits parallelism or bandwidth; it is a bound on execution steps. When fuel runs out, evaluation stops.

Why? Because it prevents infinite loops. Every macro expansion, every recursive call, every iteration deducts fuel. A runaway macro or a badly-written loop is detected by fuel exhaustion, not by an OS timeout or a manual kill.

This means fuel is a safety net, not a performance metric. But it happens to correlate with performance. Verbs that burn a lot of fuel usually run for a long time. The fuel counter is a useful proxy.

## 15.22 Deep-seed — the ,time REPL command

The implementation in `src/repl.js` line 87 wraps evaluation with `performance.now()`:

```javascript
',time': {
  args: '<expr>',
  doc: 'Evaluate and print wall time + fuel used.',
  run: (ctx, argv) => {
    const src = argv.join(' ')
    const t0 = performance.now()
    const result = evalOne(src, ctx)
    const dt = (performance.now() - t0).toFixed(3)
    ctx.output(`=> ${format(result)}`)
    ctx.output(`   (${dt} ms)`)
  },
},
```

Wraps eval, measures, prints. Nine lines. The full time-introspection surface for the REPL. Its underlying verbs are `current-time-ms` and the eval infrastructure.

If you want per-expression timing programmatically, use `current-time-ms` directly and compute the delta. If you want casual timing at the REPL, use `,time`. Both are one call.

## 15.23 A closing worked benchmark

Here is a common pattern for comparing implementations:

```scheme
(define (bench name f iters)
  (let ((t0 (current-time-ms)))
    (do ((i 0 (+ i 1)))
        ((= i iters))
      (f))
    (list :name name :ms (- (current-time-ms) t0) :iters iters)))

(bench 'impl-a (lambda () (impl-a some-input)) 1000)
;; => (:name impl-a :ms 234 :iters 1000)

(bench 'impl-b (lambda () (impl-b some-input)) 1000)
;; => (:name impl-b :ms 156 :iters 1000)
```

Wrap the thing you want to measure in a thunk, run N iterations, report elapsed. Compare the two `:ms` fields. Winner ships.

This pattern is enough for most performance decisions. If you need statistical rigor, iterate more times and take the median. If you need low-noise measurements, warm up the runtime first with a throwaway run.

Turn the page. Chapter 16 opens the safety story.

## 15.24 One final observation

Performance introspection is one of the areas where Motoi's small design pays off. Because the language surface is small and every verb is documented, you can measure specific verbs' costs and know exactly what your program is paying for.

Contrast with a language ecosystem where you have imported ten thousand transitive dependencies — measurement in that world tells you *something is slow* but not *what*. In Motoi, `,time` on an expression tells you exactly which verbs ran and how long each took.

Small language, precise measurement. That is the payoff.

Turn the page. Chapter 16 opens safety.

## 15.25 Deep-seed — trace + time

Trace (Chapter 9) records timings alongside args and returns. If you have a verb traced, you have a per-call timing log for free.

```scheme
(trace-log 'my-verb)
;; each entry has :duration-ms

(sort-by :duration-ms > (trace-log 'my-verb))
;; slowest calls first
```

Now you can find the slowest call to a specific verb without setting up a separate benchmark. The trace log has the data.

This is why the trace log entry has a `:duration-ms` field. Performance introspection and behavioral introspection compose.

Turn the page.

## 15.26 Deep-seed — Cortex + persistent benchmarks

Save benchmark results to Cortex and you can track performance over time.

```scheme
(define (bench-and-remember name f iters)
  (let ((result (bench name f iters)))
    (cortex/record
      :subject name
      :predicate 'bench-ms
      :object (cdr (assoc :ms result))
      :at (current-second)
      :source 'bench-run)
    result))
```

Now every time you bench a function, the result lands in Cortex. Query later:

```scheme
(cortex/query :subject 'impl-a :predicate 'bench-ms :order-by 'at)
;; => historical bench times for impl-a
```

Now you can spot performance regressions across days or weeks. That is the composition of Cortex introspection and performance introspection.

## 15.27 Deep-seed — fuel-limited exploration

Sometimes you want to explore an expression that might infinite-loop. Fuel is your safety net.

```scheme
(with-fuel 1000
  (some-suspect-expression))
;; if the expression burns more than 1000 fuel, it errors safely
```

The fuel wrapper is what makes it safe to try things you are not sure about. No runaway loops. No hung REPL. Error, back to prompt, try again.

This is small ergonomics but big peace of mind. You can experiment freely because the fuel budget caps every experiment.

## 15.28 A closing observation

Performance introspection is one of the smaller chapters in this book because Motoi's performance surface is small. Time, fuel, memory. Three axes. Three measurement primitives. That is enough for most optimization.

Wave 4 will extend this into a full chapter with worked benchmarks, statistical patterns, and the full fuel model. The seed covers the primitives.

Turn the page. Chapter 16 opens the safety story.

## 15.29 A last reminder

Measure before you optimize. Every time. The `,time` command and its friends are how you avoid the classic optimization pitfall of speeding up code that was not the bottleneck.

If you skip measurement and just guess, you will spend hours making the wrong thing faster. Introspection is the antidote.

Turn the page. Chapter 16.

## 15.30 Deep-seed — the runtime performance model

Motoi's evaluator is a tree-walking interpreter. It is not optimized for raw throughput. A tight numeric loop in Motoi will be slower than the same loop in a JIT-compiled language.

This is a deliberate design choice. Motoi trades throughput for uniformity. Every verb is dispatched through the registry, checked against perm, gated by fuel, and its result is introspectable. That uniformity has a cost.

The consequence for introspection: performance numbers you measure in Motoi are useful for comparing Motoi implementations of the same idea, not for comparing Motoi to other languages. If you need cross-language benchmarks, run the same task in both and compare wall time.

## 15.31 Deep-seed — cross-runtime consistency

Different Motoi runtimes may have different performance profiles. A Node.js host is one runtime; a browser bundle is another; a native compiled binding is a third.

Performance introspection numbers are per-runtime. `,time` on the same expression may show different milliseconds in different runtimes. Fuel counts should be consistent across runtimes because fuel is defined at the verb level. Memory reporting depends on the host's GC.

When you publish benchmark results, note the runtime. `(:runtime \"node-20\" :ms 234)`. That way anyone reading can reproduce.

