## 15.33 A closing worked example

For the road: a small benchmarking harness.

```scheme
(define (compare-impls impls input iters)
  (map
    (lambda (pair)
      (let ((name (car pair))
            (impl (cdr pair)))
        (bench name (lambda () (impl input)) iters)))
    impls))

(compare-impls
  (list (cons 'a impl-a) (cons 'b impl-b) (cons 'c impl-c))
  big-input
  1000)
;; => three records, sorted by :ms if you sort-by
```

Three impls compared. Winner is the smallest `:ms`. Done.

That is the kind of tool you build on top of the performance introspection primitives. Small, focused, one-shot.

Turn the page. Chapter 16 opens the safety story — the last chapter of the book, and the one that draws the honest line around what introspection can and cannot show you. Every superpower has a limit; Chapter 16 names them clearly so you can rely on both the power and the boundary in production carts, sandboxed runtimes, and stranger-code audits where trust boundaries matter most of all in practice, in production, and in front of paying users who deserve safety by design and not just by hope or by chance or by best-effort promises alone from developers who mean well but ship things that leak more often than they should.
